🔥 ASSIGNMENT 4 — FILE TRANSFER BETWEEN VIRTUAL MACHINES USING SCP
COMPLETE FINAL STEP-BY-STEP PRACTICAL SHEET
This is the clean final execution flow based on everything you actually performed successfully.

🎯 AIM
To transfer a file from one virtual machine to another using SCP (Secure Copy Protocol).

🧠 PRACTICAL SETUP
Machine	Key Pair
VM1	KP1.pem
VM2	KP2.pem
🔥 IMPORTANT CONCEPT
To transfer file:
VM1 → VM2
VM1 must have:
KP2.pem
because VM2 authenticates using its own key pair.

🌐 COMPLETE FLOW
MacBook
↓
SSH into VM1 using KP1.pem
↓
Copy KP2.pem into VM1
↓
SCP file from VM1 → VM2
↓
Verify inside VM2

✅ STEP 1 — OPEN TERMINAL
Open Mac terminal.

✅ STEP 2 — GO TO DOWNLOADS FOLDER
(Where PEM files are stored)
cd Downloads

✅ STEP 3 — FIX KP1.pem PERMISSIONS
chmod 400 KP1.pem

🎯 WHY?
AWS requires private key permissions to be restricted.
Without this: ❌ SSH login fails.

✅ STEP 4 — CONNECT TO VM1
ssh -i KP1.pem ubuntu@3.25.153.90

🧠 UNDERSTAND THIS COMMAND
Part	Meaning
ssh	Secure Shell login
-i KP1.pem	use private key
ubuntu	AWS Ubuntu username
3.25.153.90	VM1 public IP
⚠️ FIRST TIME CONNECTION
You may see:
Are you sure you want to continue connecting?
Type:
yes

🎉 SUCCESS
Terminal changes to:
ubuntu@ip-172-31-xx-xx
Meaning: ✅ connected to VM1.

✅ STEP 5 — CREATE FILE IN VM1
Inside VM1 run:
touch test.txt

✅ STEP 6 — ADD CONTENT TO FILE
Open file:
nano test.txt
Add:
Hello Cloud Computing

✅ SAVE FILE
Press:
* CTRL + O
* Enter
* CTRL + X

✅ STEP 7 — VERIFY FILE
Run:
ls
Expected:
test.txt

✅ STEP 8 — EXIT VM1
Run:
exit
Back to:
apple@MacBookPro

✅ STEP 9 — COPY KP2.pem INTO VM1
📍RUN ON MAC TERMINAL
scp -i KP1.pem KP2.pem ubuntu@3.25.153.90:/home/ubuntu

🎯 WHY THIS STEP?
VM1 needs:
KP2.pem
to authenticate into VM2.

✅ STEP 10 — LOGIN INTO VM1 AGAIN
ssh -i KP1.pem ubuntu@3.25.153.90

✅ STEP 11 — CHECK FILES
Inside VM1:
ls
Expected:
KP2.pem
test.txt

✅ STEP 12 — FIX KP2.pem PERMISSIONS
Inside VM1 run:
chmod 400 KP2.pem

🎯 WHY?
Without correct permissions: ❌ SCP/SSH authentication fails.

✅ STEP 13 — TRANSFER FILE TO VM2
Inside VM1 run:
scp -i KP2.pem test.txt ubuntu@13.239.249.62:/home/ubuntu

🧠 UNDERSTAND THIS COMMAND
Part	Meaning
scp	secure copy
-i KP2.pem	use VM2 key
test.txt	file to transfer
ubuntu	destination username
13.239.249.62	VM2 public IP
/home/ubuntu	destination path
⚠️ FIRST TIME CONNECTION
You may see:
Are you sure you want to continue connecting?
Type:
yes

🎉 SUCCESS
File transferred successfully.

✅ STEP 14 — EXIT VM1
exit

✅ STEP 15 — FIX KP2.pem PERMISSIONS ON MAC
Run on Mac:
chmod 400 KP2.pem

✅ STEP 16 — CONNECT TO VM2
Run:
ssh -i KP2.pem ubuntu@13.239.249.62

🎉 SUCCESS
Now inside VM2.

✅ STEP 17 — VERIFY FILE TRANSFER
Inside VM2 run:
ls
Expected:
test.txt
🎉 SCP practical completed successfully.

🔥 IMPORTANT COMMANDS USED
Command	Purpose
ssh	remote login
scp	secure file transfer
chmod 400	secure PEM permissions
touch	create file
nano	edit file
ls	list files
🔥 IMPORTANT EXAM CONCEPTS
Concept	Meaning
SCP	Secure Copy Protocol
SSH	Secure Shell
PEM file	private authentication key
Port 22	SSH communication port
⚠️ COMMON ERRORS + FIXES
Error	Cause	Fix
Permission denied (publickey)	wrong key	use correct PEM
UNPROTECTED PRIVATE KEY	wrong permissions	chmod 400
Connection timed out	security group issue	allow SSH
No such file	wrong path	verify filename
